                                                                                                               Sebi probe heat on merchant bankers 
          OUR BUREAU                              
	Mumbai, Jan. 11: The Securities and Exchange Board of India will probe merchant bankers associated with Satyam.         
	The mandate has fallen on Sebi general manager A. Sunil Kumar to detect the oddities. Kumar will ascertain the violations under Sebi (Merchant Bankers) Rules and Regulation, 1992.         
	Sebi has also empowered the investigating authority to seek the assistance of officers on board and any other person who shall be bound to render such assistance.         
	On January 7, the day Satyam chairman B. Ramalinga Raju confessed to his crimes, merchant banker DSP Merrill Lynch announced that it had terminated its engagement with the IT firm. DSP Merrill was brought in last month to advise on strategic options available with Satyam We, DSP Merrill Lynch Limited, have terminated our advisory engagement with Satyam Computer Services Ltd for considering various strategic options on January 6, 2009, it said in a statement.        
	In the course of such engagement, we came to understand that here were material accounting irregularities, which prompted our aforesaid decisions, the merchant banker said.        
	Earlier, Satyam had taken the services of Enam Securities as an adviser during its issue of American depository receipts. The company got listed on the New York Stock Exchange in 2001.         
	As a follow up to Satyam, Sebi on Friday said that the accounts of companies which figure on the markets bellwether indices  the sensex and the Nifty  will be picked for a peer review.        
	The review will be carried out by a panel of auditors chosen by the capital market regulator. It will cover the financial statement for the quarter ended December 31 and the last audited annual financial results.        
	The panel will review the procedures and standards followed by an auditor in preparing the financial statements of a listed entity.        
	Sebi said a few listed companies that didnt figure on the two indices would also be picked on a random basis for the review.        
	On Saturday, the Institute of Chartered Accountants of India issued a show cause notice to Satyam auditor Price Waterhouse.                                                                                                                                        
